# Adding a New Provider

Provider routing is replicated in multiple places. Adding a provider requires updating ALL of these:

1. **`api/proxy.js` — `PROVIDERS` map**
   ```js
   newprovider: {
     url: process.env.UPSTREAM_NEWPROVIDER || "https://api.newprovider.com",
     host: "api.newprovider.com",
     apiKeyEnv: "NEWPROVIDER_API_KEY",
   },
   ```

2. **`server.js` — `ROUTES` array**
   ```js
   { pattern: /^\/newprovider\/v1\/(.+)$/, provider: "newprovider" },
   ```

3. **`vercel.json` — rewrites**
   ```json
   { "source": "/newprovider/v1/:path*", "destination": "/api/proxy?provider=newprovider&path=:path*" }
   ```

4. **`cloud-functions/newprovider/v1/[[default]].js`** — EdgeOne route handler (copy from existing provider, change provider name; import from `../../shared/proxy.js`)

5. **`README.md`** — env table: document `NEWPROVIDER_API_KEY` and `UPSTREAM_NEWPROVIDER`

6. **`.env.example`** — add `NEWPROVIDER_API_KEY` and commented `UPSTREAM_NEWPROVIDER`

7. **`providerFromModel()` in `lib/models.js`** — add prefix matching if model name starts with this provider

## Reasoning handling

Reasoning helpers live in **`lib/reasoning.js`**, not `api/proxy.js`.

- DeepSeek, Kimi & MiMo: `reasoning_content` (string). MiMo gets `thinking: { type: "enabled" }` injected in `api/proxy.js`.
- Kimi K2.x (`kimi-k2.7-code`, `kimi-k2.6*`, `kimi-k2.5*`) request sanitization lives in **`lib/kimi.js`** (`sanitizeKimiBody`), called from `api/proxy.js` before `injectStoredReasoning()`. K2.7 omits `thinking`; K2.6 injects `{ type: "enabled", keep: "all" }` unless disabled; all K2.x tiers strip fixed sampling params and normalize `tool_choice`. Default Kimi model when omitted: `kimi-k2.7-code`.
- MiniMax: `reasoning_details` (object, array, or structured — sent with `reasoning_split: true`)
- If new provider has a different reasoning field, update these functions in `lib/reasoning.js`: `reasoningField()`, `readReasoning()`, `serializeReasoning()`, `deserializeReasoning()` (private), `hasReasoningField()` (private), `updateStreamReasoning()`
- Add the provider key to the `reasoningProviders` set inside `injectStoredReasoning()` if its assistant turns must carry reasoning back upstream
- Anthropic and Azure OpenAI are intentionally excluded from `reasoningProviders` (they reject `reasoning_content`)

## Vision support

- Extend `requiresVisionBridge(providerKey, bareModel)` in `api/proxy.js` if the provider lacks inline images (DeepSeek and MiniMax always return true; Kimi returns false). For mixed-capability providers (MiMo), gate on model id inside the helper.
- Also update `lib/edgeone.js` URL regex and unknown-provider error string in `api/proxy.js`.
- The vision bridge orchestration lives in `lib/vision-bridge.js` (`convertImagesToText`); the upstream HTTP call lives in `lib/vision.js` (`describeImage`). Neither needs editing for a new provider.

## Azure-specific transforms

If the new provider is an Azure Foundry deployment:

- Body sanitizers live in `lib/azure-openai.js` (`sanitizeAzureOpenAIBody`, `normalizeAzureOpenAITools`) and `lib/azure-anthropic.js` (`sanitizeAzureAnthropicBody`, `remapAnthropicInput`, `normalizeAnthropicContentTypes`)
- Response/SSE mappers live in the same files (`mapResponsesToOpenAI`, `mapResponsesSSEToOpenAI`, `mapAnthropicResponseToOpenAI`, `mapAnthropicSSEToOpenAI`)
- Add provider-specific URL construction via `buildUrl()` inside the `PROVIDERS` map in `api/proxy.js`
- Reasoning model detection logic lives in `isAzureReasoningModel()` in `lib/azure-openai.js`

## Compatible providers (openaicompat, anthropiccompat)

These are generic passthrough providers for any OpenAI- or Anthropic-compatible endpoint.

- **Route-only + alias routing**: `openaicompat` and `anthropiccompat` route via URL path (`/openaicompat/v1/...`, `/anthropiccompat/v1/...`) AND via `compatible-` model prefix aliases (`compatible-gpt-5.5` → `openaicompat`, `compatible-claude-sonnet-4-6` → `anthropiccompat`).
- **Model aliases**: defined in `COMPATIBLE_MODEL_ALIASES` in `lib/models.js`. To add new aliases, add entries to the map and they'll automatically route and resolve.
- **Anthropic response mapping**: `anthropiccompat` reuses `mapAnthropicResponseToOpenAI` / `mapAnthropicSSEToOpenAI` from `lib/azure-anthropic.js`. The `ANTHROPIC_PROVIDERS` set in that file gates `remapAnthropicInput` and `normalizeAnthropicContentTypes`.
- **Body sanitization**: `anthropiccompat` runs through `sanitizeAzureAnthropicBody` (gated by `ANTHROPIC_PROVIDERS`) to strip OpenAI-only fields (`stream_options`, etc.) and remap `instructions`→`system`, `reasoning_effort`→`output_config.effort`, `max_completion_tokens`→`max_tokens`. `openaicompat` normalizes Anthropic-flat tools (`{name, input_schema}` → `{type:"function", function:{...}}`) and is otherwise passthrough. The Azure-specific env defaults (`AZURE_ANTHROPIC_THINKING` / `AZURE_ANTHROPIC_EFFORT`) are gated to `azureanthropic` only.
- **Opt-in caching**: `OPENAICOMPAT_REASONING_CACHE=true` adds `openaicompat` to `reasoningProviders` in `lib/reasoning.js` (hit-only on miss — never fabricates placeholder reasoning, since `openaicompat` points at arbitrary endpoints whose models may reject `reasoning_content`). `ANTHROPICCOMPAT_THINKING_CACHE=true` enables Claude thinking cache for `anthropiccompat` in `api/proxy.js`.
- **Responses wire mode** (`openaicompat` only): `OPENAICOMPAT_WIRE_API=responses` (default `chat`) switches the upstream call from `/v1/chat/completions` to `/v1/responses`, reuses the generic Responses API mappers/sanitizer from `lib/azure-openai.js` (`mapResponsesToOpenAI`, `mapResponsesSSEToOpenAI`, `sanitizeAzureOpenAIBody` — gated via `isOpenAICompatResponses()` so Azure-specific env overrides don't leak), and enables codex-style `previous_response_id` chaining under a **distinct** KV namespace (`oairesp:conv:<sha>`, scope `openaicompat:v1:upstreamBase:model:user`). `OPENAICOMPAT_REASONING_EFFORT` is Responses-mode-only and forces nested `reasoning.effort`; it must not affect chat mode, Azure, or other providers. Reasoning injection (`OPENAICOMPAT_REASONING_CACHE`) is Chat-mode-only and stays excluded in Responses mode. See `.cursor/rules/azure-foundry.mdc` for the shared chaining block.
- **Do not Azure-normalize openaicompat Responses content**: `openaicompat` Responses mode must preserve official Responses `EasyInputMessage` string content such as `{role:"user", content:"hello"}`. Do **not** run `normalizeAzureOpenAIInputContent()` or wrap plain strings into Azure-style content arrays for generic compatible gateways unless the target provider is explicitly proven to require that shape. If Cursor already sends a structured content array with `{type:"text", text:"..."}`, normalize only that part type to Responses-legal `input_text` / `output_text`; upstream `/v1/responses` rejects bare `text` parts.
- **Mixed Responses tools fallback**: Cursor can send many Chat-Completions function tools plus one native Responses `custom` `apply_patch` tool. Some compatible gateways accept each shape alone but return 502 when mixed. The openaicompat Responses path may retry once after an upstream 5xx with native `custom`/`apply_patch` tools omitted, preserving the function tools. Test the first outbound body and the fallback body; do not make this Azure behavior.
- **HTTP previous_response_id may be unsupported**: Some gateways support POST `/v1/responses` but reject HTTP `previous_response_id` with `previous_response_id is only supported on Responses WebSocket v2`. The openaicompat Responses path retries once stateless with the full input array, logs `OAI_PREV_RESP_UNSUPPORTED_RETRY`, and marks only that upstream/model/user scope as stateless-only for the current process (`OAI_PREV_RESP_UNSUPPORTED_SKIP`). This is a compatibility fallback, not Codex cache. Do not disable chaining globally: providers/scopes that accept HTTP `previous_response_id` must continue using the normal `PREV_RESP_ID_FOUND` → trimmed input path.
- **Header isolation**: `anthropiccompat` uses clean `Headers()` (same as Azure providers) to prevent leaking client auth upstream.
- **Auth mode**: `anthropiccompat` supports `api-key` (default, `x-api-key`) or `bearer` (`Authorization: Bearer`) via `ANTHROPICCOMPAT_AUTH_MODE`.
- **Default model**: `OPENAICOMPAT_DEFAULT_MODEL` / `ANTHROPICCOMPAT_DEFAULT_MODEL` inject a model when the client omits it.
